            <p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="1">As a musician who has been part of several local NYC bands, as well as a DJ who produces hourlong sets designed for CD distribution (not that i ever do)... I find these rulings quite dumb.<br />
<br />
Napster killed my CD sales?  While none of mine have ever been on sale at your local Sam Goody (I dont have the time to put together professional stuff for that yet)... I can safely say that online music sharing has HELPED me.  Without Napster/Kazaa etc, my music would not be heard by people in the west coast etc.  Other week I actually got an email from someone who downloaded my last set off Kazaa from a friend of mine, and he thought it was all good.  <br />
<br />
Hrm.  Record companies do not care about musicians. They simply care about what makes them money.  Ever seen the movie Airheads?  At the end where the Lone Rangers get the record deal the company wants them to lip sync live.  They also wanted to sign them without hearing the music first.  Sad part is, that's how record companies in the US currently operate.<br />
<br />
I'm sure there are companies that don't but... few and far.</font></p>
             
